.TH CODEX_PLUGIN_REMOVE 1 "July 2026" "codex-cli 0.142.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
codex\-plugin\-remove \- Remove an installed plugin from local config and cache.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.EX
Usage: codex plugin remove [OPTIONS] <PLUGIN[@MARKETPLACE]>

.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
Remove an installed plugin from local config and cache.
.PP
Pass either `PLUGIN@MARKETPLACE` or pass `PLUGIN` with `\-\-marketplace MARKETPLACE`.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.B <PLUGIN[@MARKETPLACE]>
Plugin selector to remove: either PLUGIN@MARKETPLACE or PLUGIN with \-\-marketplace
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-c, \-\-config <key=value>
Override a configuration value that would otherwise be loaded from `~/.codex/config.toml`. Use a dotted path (`foo.bar.baz`) to override nested values. The `value` portion is parsed as TOML. If it fails to parse as TOML, the raw string is used as a literal.
.PP
Examples: \- `\-c model="o3"` \- `\-c 'sandbox_permissions=["disk\-full\-read\-access"]'` \- `\-c shell_environment_policy.inherit=all`
.TP
.B \-m, \-\-marketplace <MARKETPLACE>
Marketplace name to use when PLUGIN does not include @MARKETPLACE
.TP
.B \-\-enable <FEATURE>
Enable a feature (repeatable). Equivalent to `\-c features.<name>=true`
.TP
.B \-\-json
Output remove result as JSON
.TP
.B \-\-disable <FEATURE>
Disable a feature (repeatable). Equivalent to `\-c features.<name>=false`
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print help (see a summary with '\-h')
Examples:
.TP
.B codex plugin remove sample@debug
.TP
.B codex plugin remove sample \-\-marketplace debug
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR codex (1),
.BR codex\-plugin (1)
